snippet.textDisplay:
Soar freely.. go on, soar freely..

Liberating yourself from mere bookish wisdom
Putting on the humble earrings of the devotee of Truth

Soar freely.. soar freely..

Without your spiritual guide,
You’ll just be spurned at every door
You must take care your blessed colour doesn’t wear off
Repeating in devotion blessings on the Prophet
Submitting yourself to his tender guidance

Soar freely.. soar freely..

You go around searching for God,
but God is right here in your heart
The reality of Love is boundless as the sea
Changing your guise at the beloved’s instruction
Throttling the base desires of your heart

Soar freely.. soar freely..

The beloved, black-cloaked Prophet says
Wear the prayer-beads of ‘(nothing) except God’ around your neck
Cleanse your heart from within, O human
You won’t gain God by rubbing your forehead in prostration
You have been at pains to earn the reputation of a pious worshipper
But you have failed to remove the idol of ‘I’ from your heart
Where everything is ‘He’, there can be no possibility of ‘I’
He is nearer to us than our jugular vein;
and it was He who said ‘I am the Truth’ and went to the gallows

Soar freely.. soar freely..

Translated by Zahra Sabri

snippet.textDisplay: Mohsin Abbas Haider has a perfect Alto quality in his voice. This helps him keeping his tone clear of any dominance of instruments. This composition assimilates the message in the lyrics with the choice of Qawwali's format. The number of instruments involved is kept limited, that is clap of hands, Dhol, flute, and other fillers, which helps the meaning of the lyrics to be heard, and get absorbed easily. Some words are not Punjabi, though. In the line, " Bin Murshad De, Dar Dar Dur Dur" the word, "Bin" is Punjabized as "Bindr", which sounds strange to a Punjabi ear.
snippet.textOriginal: Mohsin Abbas Haider has a perfect Alto quality in his voice. This helps him keeping his tone clear of any dominance of instruments. This composition assimilates the message in the lyrics with the choice of Qawwali's format. The number of instruments involved is kept limited, that is clap of hands, Dhol, flute, and other fillers, which helps the meaning of the lyrics to be heard, and get absorbed easily. Some words are not Punjabi, though. In the line, " Bin Murshad De, Dar Dar Dur Dur" the word, "Bin" is Punjabized as "Bindr", which sounds strange to a Punjabi ear.
